No Neighbours: A Graph Theory Puzzle Game
No Neighbours is an interactive, web-based strategy game built to visualize the Maximum Independent Set (MIS) problem, a fundamental concept in the Design and Analysis of Algorithms (DAA).

🎮 Overview
The objective is simple: select the largest possible number of vertices in a graph without picking any two that are connected by an edge. It is a direct implementation of the "Independent Set" constraint—once a vertex is chosen, all its neighbors are disqualified.

🛠️ Tech Stack
HTML5: Structure of the game board and UI components.

CSS3: Styling for the graph nodes, edge animations, and responsive layout.

JavaScript (ES6+): Core game logic, graph generation, and algorithmic solvers.

✨ Key Features
Dynamic Graph Generation: Randomly generated networks of varying difficulty.

Real-time Constraint Mapping: Visual feedback (color changes) when a vertex and its neighbors are selected or blocked.

Algorithmic Benchmarking: Compare your manual score against a Greedy Heuristic or an Exact Backtracking solver.

Interactive UI: Smooth Canvas/DOM-based interactions for selecting nodes.

🧠 DAA Concepts Applied
Graph Representation: Utilizes Adjacency Lists for efficient neighbor lookups.

Complexity Visualization: Demonstrates why finding the Maximum Independent Set is NP-Hard.

State Management: Tracks the "Available," "Selected," and "Blocked" states of every vertex during gameplay.
